The first result in this section is that in a linear order `Œ±`, if the range of a monotone function
`f : Œ± ‚Üí Œπ` admits a least upper bound `a`, then `f` converges to `a`.

Later results specialize this to the case of (conditionally) complete linear orders, where the
existence of a least upper bound `Œ±` is automatic.  In these settings the result is that `f`
converges to its supremum, `‚®Ü i, f i`.

Here is a counter-example to show that the order must be a linear (i.e., total) order. Take
`Œ± = [0, 1) ‚Üí ‚Ñù` with the natural lattice structure; this is a `conditionally_complete_lattice`.
Take `Œπ = ‚Ñï` and `f n x = -x^n`. Then `‚®Ü n, f n = 0` while none of `f n` is strictly greater than
the constant function `-0.5`.
